England":"Mowsley, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Christ-Church, London, England":"London, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","<Of Mosely, Eastwell, Leicestershire, England>":"Eastwell, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Mousley-Eastwell, Leicester, England, Great Britain":"Mowsley, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"BRABAZON","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Old French <i>Brabançon</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>Brabanzon</i>, Middle English <i>Brab(a)son</i> ‘Brabanter’. This was originally an ethnic name for a native of the duchy of Brabant (now in north Belgium). Medieval Brabant was widely known for two exports, its brutal mercenary soldiers and its linen cloth. In the 13th century parts of France were devastated by marauding gangs of armed Brabanters, and <i>brabançon</i> came to be used generically to denote a mercenary, hired assassin, or robber. These originated in Brabant and Flanders, but in the course of time accepted recruits from anywhere. The true source of the surname is the presence in many English (and Irish) towns of Brabant cloth merchants."],"variants":[{"name":"Bravender","meanings":["English (East Yorkshire): ethnic name for someone from Brabant (Flanders). Compare   Brabazon  ."]},{"name":"Brabson","meanings":["English (Warwickshire): variant of   Brabazon  . This form is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Brabant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Aime, Aristide, Marcel, Normand, Ovila, Yvan.","French, Walloon, Flemish, and German: habitational name from Brabant, a province in the Low Countries.","English: cognate of 1 above, from Old French <i>Brabant</i>, Middle English <i>Braban</i>, <i>Brabayn</i>, used to denote both the region and an inhabitant of it. See also the synonymous   Brabazon  . In medieval England, Brabans were typically linen weavers and cloth merchants. The final syllable of <i>Braban</i>, when weakly stressed, was often altered to <i>-ben</i>, <i>-bin</i>, or <i>-bon</i>, and also to <i>-bam</i>. The additional <i>-t</i> or <i>-d</i> in post-medieval <i>Brabant</i>,   Braband  , etc. is probably excrescent, rather than a relic of the Old French form."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Lewis   or respelling of   Lou  , as borne by the impresario  Lew Grade  (  1906–98 , originally  Louis Winogradsky )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":4,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":39,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":70,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":95,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":108,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Roger le BRABAZON was born in 1220, in Eastwell, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Thomas Brabazon and Amicia Moseley. He had at least 3 sons with Beatrix Bissett. In 1313, at the age of 93, his occupation is listed as chief justice of common pleas in England, United Kingdom. He was buried in London, England."},"et":{"<1220>–":"1220–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1224–Female":"1224–Surnud","1242–1295":"1242–1295","1254–1317":"1254–1317","1258–Male":"1258–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1242":"1242","1220":"1220","1295":"1295","<1220>":"1220","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1313":"1313","1224":"1224","1254":"1254","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","East Bridgeford, Leicester, England, Great Britain":"Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Mowsley, Leicestershire, England":"Mowsley, Leicesters